We ask patients at high risk for colorectal tumors (carriers of mutations associated with hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancer) to provide stool samples prior to routine screening colonoscopy. The stool is assayed for two markers, BAT-26 and Q-DNA. Mutations in BAT-26, a marker that is sensitive to length mutations in mismatch repair deficient tumors, has been shown to be a highly informative marker for identification of MMR deficient tumors. Q-DNA is a marker that is being developed at EXACT Sciences, and will also be used to identify stool samples thought to contain neoplastic DNA. All patients entering the study will have their stool specimen analyzed by EXACT Sciences and the results compared to results of colonoscopy. Subsequently, any neoplastic tissue removed from these patients will be analyzed for BAT-26 mutations. <br><br>DNA is recovered from a fecal aliquot = 6 g by solvent extraction (which yields human DNA in essentially 100% of instances). BAT-26, a marker for microsatellite instability, is assayed; and selected primers are used to detect "Q-DNA" which includes fragments = 270 base pairs. As the stool DNA contains an abundance of human normal DNA, BAT-26 fragments that are greater, or less than 4 b.p. from the modal allele size will be scored as positive. For the Q-DNA, quantitative length differences can be measured for each assay and plotted. The most recent estimate for completing the sequence of the human genome is the end of the year 2000. Even in the absence of this “full” sequence, a variety of approaches have resulted in the identification of most if not all expressed genes. The pattern of expression, both at the level of RNA and protein, can describe the difference between cancers of different malignant potential. Genes that are specifically expressed (or differentially modified) in breast cancer may allow us to detect cancers earlier using enhanced imaging methods. Alternatively, genes that are specifically expressed by the breast epithelium (whether it be cancer or normal), may allow us to devise blood tests to detect the presence of these cells in the peripheral blood where they should not be under normal circumstances. Such a blood test could be used to detect cancer at an earlier stage or monitor the efficacy of systemic therapy. <br> Expression differences may also indicate responsiveness to specific therapies allowing us to tailor these therapies to the individual malignancy. In the case of breast cancer, this concept has been used for many years. Hormonal therapies (e.g., tamoxifen) are used primarily for tumors that express the estrogen receptor (ER) and the more recent drug, Herceptin, is used to treat cancers that overexpress the HER-2/neu growth factor receptor. ER and HER-2 are the specific targets of these therapeutic compounds and more examples like this will surely be found. However, more complex interactions of cytotoxic agents, ionizing radiation, and genetic or immune-based therapies with the cancer will likely be the norm. The ability to examine the expression of many genes at one time may allow us to uncover these interactions and improve treatment and prognostic predictions. <br> A number of technologic and methodologic advances have now made it possible to measure expression from thousands of genes in one experiment. This can be accomplished at the level of RNA and protein (using different techniques), however both approaches require high quality flash-frozen tissue. Specifically, two techniques will be employed in the context of this proposal: 1) High-density cDNA arrays to measure gene expression at the RNA level and 2) Time of flight/mass spectroscopy for measuring protein expression. Breast tissue is routinely collected by the Cancer Center Tissue Bank and stored in freezers of the Duke Breast Program. We propose to begin using these new expression based techniques for the discovery of genes that predict for the presence of breast malignancies, the aggressiveness of the disease, and the response to therapies. THIS PROTOCOL is the CR-RSB Database.</value><recordNumber>72</recordNumber><numberOfRecords>551</numberOfRecords><ontologyVersion>1.8</ontologyVersion><Identifier>72</Identifier><slot>Title</slot><value>Biomarker Dev Lab At Moffitt Supplement</value><recordNumber>73</recordNumber><numberOfRecords>551</numberOfRecords><ontologyVersion>1.8</ontologyVersion><Identifier>73</Identifier><slot>Eligibility_criteria</slot><value></value><recordNumber>74</recordNumber><numberOfRecords>551</numberOfRecords><ontologyVersion>1.8</ontologyVersion><Identifier>73</Identifier><slot>Protocol_Abstract</slot><value>Current methods for early detection of breast cancer are not optimal. Mammography has a sensitivity of 75% - 90% but the positive predictive value is low, approximately 25%. Furthermore, although resolution continues to improve, mammography is still dependent on the existence of a mass lesion. Because many breast tumors will already have metastasized by the time a mass is detectable, a significant portion of mammographically detected tumors in women undergoing regular screening will already be disseminated and incurable. Furthermore, mammography alone may not be sufficient for early detection in premenopausal women, particularly for young women with inherited susceptibility or other high risk profiles, for reasons related to breast density, tumor growth rates, and potential susceptibility to radiation-induced damage in women with germline predisposing mutations such as BRCA1/2. New methods for early detection that can serve as an adjunct to mammography are urgently needed. We are examining a novel approach that can be applied to early detection, based on comparing protein signatures in nipple aspirate fluid (NAF) and serum in women with and without breast cancer. This approach is based on the premise that women with early stages of neoplastic progression will have different patterns of protein expression that can be detected as secreted proteins shed into NAF or serum. In Years 1 and 2 we will first establish proof-of-principle by identifying breast cancer-specific protein signatures in fresh tumor tissue that contains invasive, in-situ and normal components. This will use a novel approach coupling Laser Capture Microscopy and Surface Enhanced Laser Desorption Ionization. After we have identified a consistent protein expression profile associated with malignancy we will evaluate the translational potential of this approach by determining whether these profiles can be distinguished in conventiently accessed body fluids, i.e. NAF and serum, from women with normal breasts, ductal carcinoma in-situ (DCIS), and early (stage I) invasive cancer. This will help determine the stage of neoplastic progression when early detection based on this approach is feasible. We have extensive data demonstrating the feasibility of this approach and our ability to enroll patients and obtain
